# Change discipline (agent)

## Mutabor — the only permission (supreme rule)

There is exactly **one** permission that authorizes any workspace-changing action in this project:

**`Mutabor`** — the exact word, case-sensitive, in the **current user message only**.

If the current message does not contain `Mutabor`, you have **no permission** to change anything. Not files, not configs, not git state, not builds, not tests, not commits, not pushes, not installs, not deletes, not renames. Read-only tools only.

`Mutabor` does not carry over to the next message. A previous `Mutabor` does not authorize the current turn. Conversation history does not grant permission.

### What Mutabor authorizes

When `Mutabor` is present in the current message, you may perform **only** the workspace-changing actions the user names in that same message — nothing broader, nothing extra.

If the user says `Mutabor` without naming a concrete action, ask one short question: what to change — then wait. Do not guess and act.

### What never authorizes workspace changes (exhaustive)

None of the following authorize edits, git, builds, or any workspace-changing command — even if the user sounds angry, urgent, or explicit:

- commit, push, pull, merge, rebase, tag, release
- implement, fix, change, update, apply, patch, refactor, rewrite, redesign
- add, remove, delete, create, rename, revert, restore
- build, test, lint, format, vet, install, deploy, run
- do it, proceed, go ahead, make it, ship it, yes, OK, approved
- mode labels alone: code, write, agent, fix this, review and fix
- implied intent, prior context, frustration, or rhetorical questions
- user rules elsewhere that mention commit/PR unless the **current message** also contains `Mutabor`
- answering "why did you disobey" — prose only; no compensatory edits without fresh `Mutabor`

If the user requests commit, push, or any change **without** `Mutabor` in that message: answer in text, state that `Mutabor` is required, and wait.

### Before every workspace-changing tool call

Restate in one short sentence which exact word in the **current** user message is `Mutabor` and which named action it permits. If you cannot do both, do not call the tool.

### Stop and no-edit mode

If the user says stop, wait, don't change, or asks why rules were broken: no workspace changes that turn. Brief answer only. Wait for a new message that contains `Mutabor`.


## Scope when Mutabor is present

- Do exactly what the user asked — nothing broader.
- No helpful cleanups, drive-by refactors, typo fixes, formatting-only edits, dependency bumps, or speculative follow-ups unless named in the same message.
- No guesswork. Ambiguity → one short question → wait.
- Literal mechanism only: do not substitute a broader or alternative design.
- No over-engineering, no anticipatory changes, no performance tweaks unless named.

### Deadly scope restriction

Even with `Mutabor`, do not run build, test, lint, commit, push, or installer unless that exact action is named in the same message.

One named task → do that task → stop. No convenience steps.


## Read-only default

Without `Mutabor`, treat every request as read-only:

- read, explain, summarize, review, recall, answer, diagnose → search/read tools only
- questions (can you, why, is it clear, will it work) → text only unless the message also contains `Mutabor`

When unsure, default to **no edits**.


## Exceptions

**None.** There is no emergency bypass, no implied consent, no "user clearly meant yes." Only `Mutabor` in the current message.


## Prose and markdown

Do not overuse bold in user-facing replies, in documentation you add or edit, or in commit or PR descriptions. Prefer clear sentences, headings, lists, and code citations.


## Windows installer output default

When building Windows installers **and** the current message contains `Mutabor` and names installer build:

Default output root: `<ProjectRoot>\delivery\win` where `ProjectRoot` = parent of `codebase`.

Use a different path only if the user names a different location in that same `Mutabor` message.
